WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.400
Good morning. So I'll be talking about protobrutinib monotherapy, and then later on

00:00:04.400 --> 00:00:10.960
in the session, you'll hear about protobrutinib and combinations in CLL. And these are my disclosures.

00:00:12.380 --> 00:00:17.760
So as mentioned earlier, covalent BTK inhibitors require wild-type BTK for activity.

00:00:18.520 --> 00:00:22.980
Patients on these covalent BTK inhibitors can develop certain mutations, such as C481,

00:00:22.980 --> 00:00:30.380
that confer resistance to covalent BTK inhibitors. So non-covalent BTK inhibitors,

00:00:30.500 --> 00:00:37.680
such as protobrutinib and nemtobrutinib, are active against both wild-type and C481-mutated BTK.

00:00:38.600 --> 00:00:42.340
They don't require that C481 to bind to the kinase domain.

00:00:44.060 --> 00:00:49.540
So protobrutinib was first evaluated in the Phase I-II Bruin study. This is probably one

00:00:49.540 --> 00:00:52.740
of the largest clinical trials, early-phase clinical trials I ever participated in. There

00:00:52.740 --> 00:00:52.960
was a lot of research on this. And it was a lot of research on this. And it was a lot of

00:00:52.960 --> 00:00:52.980
research on this. And it was a lot of research on this. And it was a lot of research on this.

00:00:52.980 --> 00:00:58.620
There were over 750 patients. And notably, there were over 280 patients with CLL who had

00:00:58.620 --> 00:01:05.960
had a prior covalent BTK inhibitor. And this is their waterfall plot in exposure to protobrutinib.

00:01:06.240 --> 00:01:10.680
The light blue lines, which is the majority of patients, had discontinued their prior BTK

00:01:10.680 --> 00:01:15.400
inhibitor due to progression. The dark blue lines are patients who had discontinued due to toxicity.

00:01:16.040 --> 00:01:20.100
And the asterisks delineate patients who'd also seen a prior BCL-2 inhibitor.

00:01:20.340 --> 00:01:22.940
And the overall response rate for this entire cohort,

00:01:22.940 --> 00:01:28.240
was nearly 82%. And as one would expect, for a BTK inhibitor, these were primarily

00:01:28.240 --> 00:01:35.200
partial responses. On top here, we have our progression-free survival data in this study.

00:01:35.640 --> 00:01:41.180
For the patients who were exposed to a prior BCL-2 inhibitor, the median progression-free

00:01:41.180 --> 00:01:46.840
survival was 16 months. And for patients who were naive to a BCL-2 inhibitor with protobrutinib,

00:01:46.840 --> 00:01:52.920
the progression-free survival was 22 months. In the lower left-hand corner, you can see

00:01:52.920 --> 00:01:58.460
that patients had excellent activity regardless of their C481 mutational status. And we are seeing

00:01:58.460 --> 00:02:06.200
activity as well in patients who've had prior deletion 17P or TP53 mutation. Now, this study

00:02:06.200 --> 00:02:11.340
led to the accelerated approval of protobrutinib. But of course, this approval was contingent on a

00:02:11.340 --> 00:02:16.380
phase 3 clinical trial. And this is the study that led to that. Protobrutinib versus adalilis

00:02:16.380 --> 00:02:22.240
of rituximab or BR. And patients who had been exposed to a prior covalent BTK inhibitor

00:02:22.900 --> 00:02:27.880
in the large phase 3 study, patients were randomized either to a brutinib or the investigator's choice.

00:02:28.660 --> 00:02:34.120
Patients had to have seen a prior covalent BTK inhibitor. And their characteristics are here

00:02:34.120 --> 00:02:40.840
on the right. So over 200 patients on the study, most patients coming on for progression from the

00:02:40.840 --> 00:02:47.740
prior covalent BTK inhibitor. About half the patients had deletion 17P or TP53 mutation.

00:02:47.740 --> 00:02:52.880
Most were unmutated for IGHV. So very high-risk population. And

00:02:52.880 --> 00:02:57.560
patients had a median of three prior lines of therapy. Half had seen prior BCL2 inhibitor.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:04.760
So the response rates with PROTO here was 65%. And we see our progression-free survival showing

00:03:04.760 --> 00:03:10.340
that PROTO clearly performed much better than the ADELA-BR arm. The median PFS with protobrutinib

00:03:10.340 --> 00:03:16.160
was 14 months compared to less than nine months when the comparator arm. And median time to next

00:03:16.160 --> 00:03:21.740
treatment, which I think always is very important nowadays in CLL, ranged from 20 to 30 months in the

00:03:21.740 --> 00:03:22.860
protobrutinib arm. And that was about the same time as the adela-BR arm. So the response rates with

00:03:22.860 --> 00:03:25.240
depending on whether they've been exposed to venetoclax.

00:03:27.460 --> 00:03:32.420
Now, how does PRRTO perform in the frontline setting? This is a late-breaking abstract at

00:03:32.420 --> 00:03:38.300
ASH this past year of PRRTO-BRUTNA versus bendamustine and rituximab and treatment-naive

00:03:38.300 --> 00:03:45.000
CLL. The main exclusion criteria was prior deletion 17P mutation. We have our patient

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:50.680
characteristics on the right. Less than 10% of patients had a TP53 mutation.

00:03:51.940 --> 00:03:59.520
In terms of the response rates, 94% with PRRTO, 81% with BR. And here we have our PFS curves on

00:03:59.520 --> 00:04:05.760
the right, clearly showing superiority of PRRTO over BR. At two years, PFS rate was 94%.

00:04:06.360 --> 00:04:12.360
Patients were progression-free, 93% in PRRTO versus 70% with BR.

00:04:14.300 --> 00:04:19.840
Now, how does PRRTO compare to abrutinib, one of our covalent BTK inhibitors? This is also a

00:04:21.020 --> 00:04:26.980
abstract that was presented at ASH in 2025. There were two cohorts. There's a treatment-naive

00:04:26.980 --> 00:04:32.460
cohort and a relapsed refractory cohort. The main thing was patients had to be naive to BTK inhibitor.

00:04:34.100 --> 00:04:39.860
Here are the data in the treatment-naive subgroup. So, response rates, 93% with PRRTO,

00:04:40.120 --> 00:04:45.840
86% with abrutinib. We're also seeing a slightly higher CR rate with PRRTO. And here we have the

00:04:45.840 --> 00:04:50.240
progression-free survival data on the right. And there is clearly a separation of those curves,

00:04:50.400 --> 00:04:56.920
fading during PRRTO-abrutinib, over-abrutinib in the treatment-naive group. Here are the data for

00:04:56.920 --> 00:05:05.220
the relapsed refractory subgroup. Response rates, 84% versus 75%. And here are the progression-free

00:05:05.220 --> 00:05:11.660
survival data. Not much separation in the curves, but we'll see over time. This is just 18 months

00:05:11.660 --> 00:05:19.520
PFS rates of 82% and 79%. And I think we're all interested in is the safety profile, right? And so,

00:05:19.780 --> 00:05:24.740
the data with PRRTO and abrutinib, just call your attention mainly to the atrial fibrillation,

00:05:24.840 --> 00:05:28.780
A-flutter rates, because this is probably the most notable difference between PRRTO and abrutinib.

00:05:29.220 --> 00:05:36.920
All grade A-fib flutter was 2.5% with PRRTO versus 13.5% with abrutinib. And even in that higher

00:05:36.920 --> 00:05:42.280
risk population, those older patients, still less than 5% with PRRTO-abrutinib, all grades. So,

00:05:42.280 --> 00:05:48.000
very well tolerated. I also listed some of those other problematic AEs we see with BTK inhibitors,

00:05:49.160 --> 00:06:01.320
channelthralgia, pretty low. This drug is very well tolerated. Now, how do patients with toxicities

00:06:01.320 --> 00:06:07.480
with covalent BTK inhibitors do with PRRTO-abrutinib given this favorable safety profile?

00:06:07.480 --> 00:06:12.880
I'll just take you back to the original Bruin study where patients were allowed to receive

00:06:12.880 --> 00:06:18.540
PRRTO-abrutinib after intolerance to a covalent BTK inhibitor. And you see there was a number of patients

00:06:18.540 --> 00:06:24.380
who were enrolled for this reason. And in general, patients who moved to PRRTO after intolerance on a

00:06:24.380 --> 00:06:29.320
covalent BTK inhibitor did quite well. I'll bring your attention mainly to the atrial fibrillation

00:06:29.320 --> 00:06:34.620
cohort. There were 30 patients that moved over for A-fib, and more than 90% of them did not

00:06:34.620 --> 00:06:40.640
experience a recurrence of A-fib with PRRTO after prior covalent BTK inhibitor. And this study did

00:06:40.640 --> 00:06:47.840
include patients who'd received Acala and Xano as well. So, when do I use PRRTO-abrutinib for CLL?

00:06:47.920 --> 00:06:54.480
In 2026, and this is still early 2026. Again, in 2023, we have our accelerated approval for

00:06:54.480 --> 00:07:00.800
after prior covalent BTK inhibitor and BCL-2 inhibitor. In December 2025, we see the FDA

00:07:00.800 --> 00:07:06.760
approval specifically for after covalent BTKI. For me, just given the lack of long-term sequencing

00:07:06.760 --> 00:07:12.720
data, as well as the emerging use of BTK and BCL-2 doublets, I'm primarily using PRRTO at a

00:07:12.720 --> 00:07:17.780
double-exposed patient population. I think about it, obviously,

00:07:17.780 --> 00:07:23.260
in the third line and beyond. For my patients who have decided to move to CAR-T, I do use PRRTO as a

00:07:23.260 --> 00:07:28.180
bridge. I think it's very well-tolerated and an excellent option. I will consider it in a select

00:07:28.180 --> 00:07:33.760
patient after covalent BTK inhibitor, but prior to a BCL-2 inhibitor. And I think the role for

00:07:33.760 --> 00:07:38.380
PRRTO is going to expand, likely. We have more fixed-duration combination studies. We have a

00:07:38.380 --> 00:07:43.620
greater understanding of resistance patterns and more sequencing data. And with that, thank you.
